                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/1024</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of the Third Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Long</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-09-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 26, 1919</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Debuchi called and said that he was instructed by his Government to say that
                    there were several points in the communication <pb facs="0825" n="723"
                        xml:id="pg_723"/> sent at the direction of the President in regard to
                    Shantung which the Japanese Government would take up, but that Viscount Chinda
                    had carried on the negotiations in regard to Shantung in Paris, and that it was
                    necessary for his Government to communicate with him, and that consequently
                    there would be some further delay in answering the note of the President.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Breckinridge Long</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
